section.p:
It might be the case that range does not adequately describe the spread of a data set.  Consider the two data sets \{ 0, 1, 50, 99, 100 \} and \{0, 49, 50, 51, 100 \}.  Both have a rangle of 100, but data in the first set is concentrated near 0 and 100, while data in the second set is concentrated near the mean of 50.  A better way to quantify the spread is to compute the standard deviation.  Given a data set \{x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n\} the standard deviation of this data set is
        	s = \sqrt{ \frac{(x_1 - \overline{x})^2 + (x_2 - \overline{x})^2 + \cdots (x_n - \overline{x})^2}{n}}
        Essentially, we are just averaging the squares of the deviations x_1 - \overline{x} and then taking the square root of this average.  A high standard deviation means that the data is spread out.  A low standard deviation means that the data is centered around the mean.
